Afro Nation Expands to US, Recruits Burna Boy and WizKid to Headline Inaugural Afro Nation Miami

•
 
The World's Biggest Afrobeats Festival Arrives at LoanDepot Park in Miami, FL on May 27 & 28, 2023

•

The Announcement:
Uniting the diaspora with brilliant music and breathtaking spectacle, Afro Nation is the world's biggest showcase for one of the fastest growing genres on the planet. Following successful festivals in Africa, Europe, and the Caribbean, Afro Nation takes the next step with Afro Nation Miami 2023, its first festival in the continental USA. Like previous Afro Nation events, the upcoming Miami festival highlights the best in Afrobeats, dancehall, hip-hop, amapiano, and other Black-led musical genres. Headlined by Afrobeats giants Burna Boy and WizKid, and featuring a powerful lineup of artists from Africa, the Caribbean, and across the globe, Afro Nation Miami touches down at LoanDepot Park on May 27 & 28, 2023.

Afro Nation Miami boasts a deep lineup that illustrates the diversity and strength of global Black music. The inaugural Miami festival promises performances from ascendant Nigerian superstars Rema and Asake, dancehall legend Beenie Man, rising African stars CKay, BNXN, and Black Sherif, French rapper Franglish, and many others. Shining a special spotlight on the ascendant genre of amapiano, born in South Africa, Afro Nation Miami brings the Piano People stage, headlined by Major League DJZ and Uncle Waffles, and featuring many more of the genre's most exciting names.
Congratulations to @heisrema @selenagomez @mavinrecords 🫶🏽 #Afrobeats #CalmDown

Today, Afro Nation announces that it will make its debut in one of the most significant cities in the history of Black music with Afro Nation Detroit 2023, which promises performances from some of the biggest names in Afrobeats and superstars in Hip-Hop, R&B, Amapiano, Dancehall, Reggae, and other African, Afro-Caribbean, and African-American musical genres.

•

The festival will be touching down in Detroit on August 19th and 20th, at the historic Douglass Site in Detroit, MI, for a weekend filled with additional activations and events to honor Detroit’s musical contributions to the world and highlight its connection to present day American, African, and global Black culture and music. The Douglass site is a historically significant housing project in Detroit that was the first federally funded housing project for African Americans in the United States. It was home to icons such as Diana Ross, Smokey Robinson, and other influential African Americans.

The nine-track EP, a sequel to 2019’s CLEAR EP, boasts a starry lineup of A-list collaborators such as Childish Gambino and J. Cole and production work from Solange, Steve Lacy, John Kirby and Jay Versace.

Today for a well-overdue catchup, I went to Manhattan to spend time with Nish. She had an interview with 1da Banton, an incredible Nigerian star singer-producer who recently signed a global deal with Sony Music Publishing! After their chat, we went to have a meal in the area and went to a Nike event across the bridge in Brooklyn! 

•

On the way to the function, as we crossed the bridge, we listened to Power 105.1. Fate would have it that we tuned into Nyla Symone's show, and she played several Afrobeats/Afrofusion records (Asake, Lojay) and premiered Burna Boy's new record 'Sittin' On Top of the World'. Unbeknownst to me, Symone said my name on air. Unfortunately, we didn't get to record it, but it felt good!

•

If you met me a decade ago, I was the lady hopping from city to city telling everyone I met about modern African music—so much so that I became that "the woman always talking about Africa". It used to piss people off, LOL. 

•

We all dreamed and prayed about moments like this (and worked hard as hell toward it), too. Over time, I met my "tribe". It is one of the most beautiful things ever. #ItTakesAVillage

•

Thank you to everyone who played a record, profiled an artist, interviewed them, or showed interest and took a chance on Africa and its artists. And if you're still learning, we love you too, and we are here to teach and demystify what you may not know or understand. The creators are ready to share/tell their stories.

•

It’s my birthday and I’ll cry if I want to, or whatever Lesley Gore said on that Quincy Jones-produced monster hit 🤭😂

•

Seriously though, I decided to use this picture (taken by @sfisoheromtetwa) for today’s post because I think it’s the best depiction of me—I am always in a new place, learning about each culture, and using that information to make myself better and refine my mind (unlearning). Some of the information is very painful bringing me to tears (I’m an empath), but it’s still necessary to know history (even when it hurts). It’s good for me.

•

In closing, I want all of you to know that I appreciate every single text message, voice note, and every birthday carol received. Thank you from all sections of my heart and soul 🙏🏽 

•

May the Almighty God in his divinity continue to guide me, teach me, and to mould me into whomever I need to be for my family and then, for the world.
